  "raw": "CONCORD - Feedback\n\n- The utility buttons, bug report, stats, and help need to be attached to the top bar near the user icon rather than in the pane.\n\n- make the settings menu comprehensive. I should be able to navigate server settings and regular settings in one interface with clear distinctions.\n\n- make sure that when I send a message my pane is properly scrolled to the bottom of the chat display.\n\n- we need to get the native builds ready to build and test. build a native arch application for the concorrd frontened\n\n- I need to confirm my understanding. the plan for concord is a native application on all platforms right?\n\n- I need the native application goal to come sooner rather than later. Do everything you can to do the work on orrion and anything that needs to be done on orrpheus for apple reasons should be delegated there.\n\n- the dashboard bar at the bottom of the small display (mobile) takes up space that the user needs. collapse that entire rown to a handful of cucumber shapes so the user can navigate between if they know the labels, or they can close their keyboard/click on the buttons in otder to see the dash\n\n   - the bar for bug reports, stats and help also takes up valuable real estate\n\n   - both of these need to move or be collapsed when in the focused view on mobile\n\n- the keyboard should be flagged to use the return button to move to the next line rather than send the message. The user presses the send button to send. The return button goes to the next line\n\n- add make it easy for openclaw to create and present visual presentations like charts",
  "optimized": "### OPT-001: Move utility buttons to top bar\nRelocate Bug Report, Stats, and Help buttons from their current pane into the top bar, adjacent to the user icon. Remove the standalone utility row.\n\nSource: Raw #1, Raw #6 sub-bullet (utility bar real estate)\n\n### OPT-002: Unified comprehensive settings menu\nBuild a single settings interface that exposes both server settings and user/regular settings, with clear visual separation between the two scopes. Navigation between them must live in one menu.\n\nSource: Raw #2\n\n### OPT-003: Auto-scroll chat to bottom on send\nEnsure the chat pane scrolls to the bottom whenever the local user sends a message. Verify against rapid sends and long message history.\n\nSource: Raw #3\n\n### OPT-004: Native frontend build (priority, orrion-first)\nProduce a native architecture build of the Concord frontend, ready to build and test. Treat this as high priority — pull in sooner rather than later. Do all feasible work on orrion (Linux/Arch). Delegate only Apple/macOS-specific tasks (codesigning, notarization, .app/.dmg packaging, M1 testing) to orrpheus.\n\nSource: Raw #4 + Raw #5 (merged — same goal, #5 contributes priority and machine delegation constraints)\n\n### OPT-005: Mobile dashboard bar collapse to pill nav\nOn mobile/small displays, collapse the bottom dashboard bar into a compact row of pill-shaped buttons (\"cucumber shapes\" — small rounded pills) so it consumes minimal vertical space. Users who know the labels can navigate via the pills; dismissing the keyboard or tapping a pill expands the dashboard view. Apply the same collapse behavior to the bug report/stats/help bar in mobile focused view.\n\nNote: complements OPT-001 (which moves utilities to top bar on desktop). On mobile, OPT-001's destination may not exist — confirm placement strategy with the user if the top bar is also constrained on small screens.\n\nSource: Raw #6 (main + sub-bullet)\n\n### OPT-006: Return key inserts newline, send button sends\nConfigure the message input so the Return/Enter key inserts a newline instead of sending. Sending happens only via the explicit Send button. Apply on both desktop and mobile keyboards (set mobile input enterKeyHint accordingly).\n\nSource: Raw #7\n\n### OPT-007: Chart and visual presentation support for openclaw\nAdd a mechanism that lets openclaw easily create and present visual presentations such as charts inside Concord messages. Define a render path (e.g., chart spec embedded in a message that the client renders) and ship it.\n\nSource: Raw #8\n\n---\n\n## Status inquiry (not routed — answered directly)\n\n> \"I need to confirm my understanding. the plan for concord is a native application on all platforms right?\"\n\nYes — per the routing in OPT-004, the Concord plan is native applications on all target platforms: Linux/Arch built on orrion, macOS-specific work (codesign, .app/.dmg, M1 testing) delegated to orrpheus, with mobile considerations as separate items. Confirm or reject below to proceed.",
